# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: 16th-united-states-congress
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:16th-united-states-congress/100th-united-states-congress-p01] The **100th United States Congress** was a meeting of the legislative branch of the United States federal government, composed of the United States Senate and the United States House of Representatives.
[src:16th-united-states-congress/100th-united-states-congress-p01] It met in Washington, D.C., from January 3, 1987, to January 3, 1989, during the last two years of Ronald Reagan's presidency.
[src:16th-united-states-congress/100th-united-states-congress-p01] The apportionment of seats in the House of Representatives was based on the 1980 United States census.
[src:16th-united-states-congress/100th-united-states-congress-p01] This is the most recent Congress with a Democratic senator from the state of Mississippi, John C.
[src:16th-united-states-congress/100th-united-states-congress-p01] Stennis, who retired at the end of Congress, and a Republican senator from the state of Connecticut, Lowell Weicker, who lost re-election in 1988.
[src:16th-united-states-congress/100th-united-states-congress-p01] Both chambers had a Democratic majority, with the Democrats increasing their lead in the House, and regaining the Senate for the first time since the 96th Congress from 1979 to 1981.
[src:16th-united-states-congress/100th-united-states-congress-p01] This list is arranged by chamber, then by state.
[src:16th-united-states-congress/100th-united-states-congress-p01] Senators are listed by class, and representatives are listed by district.
[src:16th-united-states-congress/100th-united-states-congress-p02] Lists of committees and their party leaders for members of the House and Senate committees can be found through the Official Congressional Directory at the bottom of this article.
[src:16th-united-states-congress/100th-united-states-congress-p02] The directory after the pages of terms of service lists committees of the Senate, House (Standing with Subcommittees, Select and Special) and Joint and, after that, House/Senate committee assignments.
[src:16th-united-states-congress/100th-united-states-congress-p02] On the committees section of the House and Senate in the Official Congressional Directory, the committee's members on the first row on the left side shows the chairman of the committee and on the right side shows the ranking member of the committee.
[src:16th-united-states-congress/101st-united-states-congress-p01] The **101st United States Congress** was a meeting of the legislative branch of the United States federal government, composed of the United States Senate and the United States House of Representatives.
[src:16th-united-states-congress/101st-united-states-congress-p01] It met in Washington, D.C., from January 3, 1989, to January 3, 1991, during the final weeks of Ronald Reagan's presidency and the first two years of George H.
[src:16th-united-states-congress/101st-united-states-congress-p01] The apportionment of seats in this House of Representatives was based on the 1980 United States census.
[src:16th-united-states-congress/101st-united-states-congress-p01] Both chambers maintained a Democratic majority.
[src:16th-united-states-congress/101st-united-states-congress-p01] Senators are listed in order of seniority, and representatives are listed by district.
[src:16th-united-states-congress/101st-united-states-congress-p01] The names of representatives are preceded by their district numbers.
[src:16th-united-states-congress/102nd-united-states-congress-p01] The **102nd United States Congress** was a meeting of the legislative branch of the United States federal government, composed of the United States Senate and the United States House of Representatives.
[src:16th-united-states-congress/102nd-united-states-congress-p01] It met in Washington, D.C., from January 3, 1991, to January 3, 1993, during the last two years of George H.
[src:16th-united-states-congress/102nd-united-states-congress-p01] This is the most recent Congress where Republicans held a Senate seat from California.
[src:16th-united-states-congress/103rd-united-states-congress-p01] The **103rd United States Congress** was a meeting of the legislative branch of the United States federal government, composed of the United States Senate and the United States House of Representatives.
[src:16th-united-states-congress/103rd-united-states-congress-p01] It met in Washington, D.C. from January 3, 1993, to January 3, 1995, during the final weeks of George H.
[src:16th-united-states-congress/103rd-united-states-congress-p01] Bush's presidency and in the first two years of Bill Clinton's presidency.
[src:16th-united-states-congress/103rd-united-states-congress-p01] The apportionment of seats in the House of Representatives was based on the 1990 United States census.
[src:16th-united-states-congress/103rd-united-states-congress-p01] This is the most recent Congress to have a Democratic senator from Texas, Bob Krueger, who lost election to finish Lloyd Bentsen's term in 1993.
[src:16th-united-states-congress/103rd-united-states-congress-p01] Along with two Democratic senators from the state of Tennessee, Jim Sasser and Harlan Mathews.
[src:16th-united-states-congress/103rd-united-states-congress-p01] Jim Sasser lost re-election and Harlan Mathews retired in 1994.
[src:16th-united-states-congress/103rd-united-states-congress-p01] In addition, a Democratic senator from the state of Oklahoma, David Boren, resigned in the final weeks of the Congress.
[src:16th-united-states-congress/103rd-united-states-congress-p01] Both chambers maintained a Democratic majority, and with Bill Clinton being sworn in as president on January 20, 1993, this gave the Democrats an overall federal government trifecta for the first time since the 96th Congress in 1979.
[src:16th-united-states-congress/104th-united-states-congress] The **104th United States Congress** was a meeting of the legislative branch of the United States federal government, composed of the United States Senate and the United States House of Representatives.
[src:16th-united-states-congress/104th-united-states-congress] It met in Washington, D.C. from January 3, 1995, to January 3, 1997, during the third and fourth years of Bill Clinton's presidency.
[src:16th-united-states-congress/104th-united-states-congress] Apportionment of seats in the House of Representatives was based on the 1990 United States census.
[src:16th-united-states-congress/104th-united-states-congress] Both chambers had Republican majorities for the first time since the 83rd Congress in 1953.
[src:16th-united-states-congress/104th-united-states-congress] Major events included passage of elements of the Contract with America and a budget impasse between Congress and the Clinton administration that resulted in the federal government shutdown of 1995 and 1996.
[src:16th-united-states-congress/104th-united-states-congress] In this Congress, Class 2 meant their term ended with this Congress, requiring re-election in 1996; Class 3 meant their term began in the last Congress, requiring re-election in 1998; and Class 1 meant their term began in this Congress, requiring re-election in 2000.
[src:16th-united-states-congress/105th-united-states-congress] The **105th United States Congress** was a meeting of the legislative branch of the United States federal government, composed of the United States Senate and the United States House of Representatives.
[src:16th-united-states-congress/105th-united-states-congress] It met in Washington, DC from January 3, 1997, to January 3, 1999, during the fifth and sixth years of Bill Clinton's presidency.
[src:16th-united-states-congress/105th-united-states-congress] This is the most recent Congress with a Republican senator from New York, Al D'Amato, who lost re-election in 1998, and a Democratic senator from Kentucky, Wendell Ford, who retired at the end of the Congress.
[src:16th-united-states-congress/105th-united-states-congress] Both chambers retained a Republican majority.
[src:16th-united-states-congress/105th-united-states-congress] President Clinton was impeached by the US House of Representatives of the 105th Congress.
[src:16th-united-states-congress/105th-united-states-congress] There was no change in the parties during this Congress.
[src:16th-united-states-congress/105th-united-states-congress] In this Congress, Class 3 meant their term ended with this Congress, facing re-election in 1998; Class 1 meant their term began in the last Congress, facing re-election in 2000; and Class 2 meant their term began in this Congress, facing re-election in 2002.
[src:16th-united-states-congress/105th-united-states-congress] Representatives are listed by districts.
[src:16th-united-states-congress/105th-united-states-congress] There were no changes in Senate membership during this Congress.
[src:16th-united-states-congress/105th-united-states-congress] Four members of the House of Representatives died, and four resigned.
[src:16th-united-states-congress/106th-united-states-congress] The **106th United States Congress** was a meeting of the legislative branch of the United States federal government, composed of the United States Senate and the United States House of Representatives.
[src:16th-united-states-congress/106th-united-states-congress] It met in Washington, D.C., from January 3, 1999, to January 3, 2001, during the last two years of Bill Clinton's presidency.
[src:16th-united-states-congress/106th-united-states-congress] Both chambers maintained a Republican majority.
[src:16th-united-states-congress/106th-united-states-congress] This is the most recent Congress with Republican senators from the states of Delaware (William Roth), Michigan (Spencer Abraham) and Washington (Slade Gorton), all of whom lost re-election in 2000.
[src:16th-united-states-congress/106th-united-states-congress] It was the first Congress where Baby boomers comprised the majority of the House of Representatives.
[src:16th-united-states-congress/106th-united-states-congress] There were two resignations and three deaths.
[src:16th-united-states-congress/106th-united-states-congress] In this Congress, Class 1 meant their term ended with this Congress, facing re-election in 2000; Class 2 meant their term began in the last Congress, facing re-election in 2002; and Class 3 meant their term began in this Congress, facing re-election in 2004.
[src:16th-united-states-congress/106th-united-states-congress] In October 2000, the United States Congress passed a Sense of Congress resolution that McVay's record should reflect that "he is exonerated for the loss of the USS Indianapolis." President Clinton also signed the resolution, which rightented the miscarriage of justice on Charles B.
[src:16th-united-states-congress/106th-united-states-congress] McVay III for the sinking of the USS Indianapolis in 30 July 1945 by Japanese submarine I-58 (1943).
[src:16th-united-states-congress/16th-united-states-congress] The **16th United States Congress** was a meeting of the legislative branch of the United States federal government, consisting of the United States Senate and the United States House of Representatives.
[src:16th-united-states-congress/16th-united-states-congress] It met in Washington, D.C. from March 4, 1819, to March 4, 1821, during the third and fourth years of James Monroe's presidency.
[src:16th-united-states-congress/16th-united-states-congress] The apportionment of seats in the House of Representatives was based on the 1810 United States census.
[src:16th-united-states-congress/16th-united-states-congress] Both chambers had a Democratic-Republican majority.
[src:16th-united-states-congress/16th-united-states-congress] The count below identifies party affiliations at the beginning of the first session of this congress.
[src:16th-united-states-congress/16th-united-states-congress] Changes resulting from subsequent replacements are shown below in the "Changes in membership" section.
[src:16th-united-states-congress/16th-united-states-congress] During this congress, two Senate seats were added for each of the new states of Alabama and Maine.
[src:16th-united-states-congress/16th-united-states-congress] During this congress, one House seat was added for the new state of Alabama and one seat was reapportioned from Massachusetts to the new state of Maine.
[src:16th-united-states-congress/16th-united-states-congress] For the beginning of the next congress, six more seats from Massachusetts would be reapportioned to Maine.
[src:16th-united-states-congress/16th-united-states-congress] Senators are listed by class and representatives are listed by district.
[src:16th-united-states-congress/16th-united-states-congress] Senators were elected by the state legislatures every two years, with one-third beginning new six-year terms with each Congress.
[src:16th-united-states-congress/16th-united-states-congress] Preceding the names in the list below are Senate class numbers, which indicate the cycle of their election.
[src:16th-united-states-congress/16th-united-states-congress] In this Congress, Class 1 meant their term ended with this Congress, requiring re-election in 1820; Class 2 meant their term began in the last Congress, requiring re-election in 1822; and Class 3 meant their term began in this Congress, requiring re-election in 1824.
[src:16th-united-states-congress/16th-united-states-congress] The count below reflects changes from the beginning of this Congress.
[src:16th-united-states-congress/16th-united-states-congress] There were 5 resignations, 2 deaths, 2 vacancies before the Congress, and 4 new seats.
[src:16th-united-states-congress/16th-united-states-congress] The Democratic-Republicans had a 7-seat net gain and the Federalists had a 1-seat net loss.
[src:16th-united-states-congress/16th-united-states-congress] There were 13 resignations, 5 deaths, 2 contested elections, and 2 new seats.
[src:16th-united-states-congress/16th-united-states-congress] The Democratic-Republicans had a 1-seat net gain and the Federalists had no net change.
[src:16th-united-states-congress/16th-united-states-congress] Lists of committees and their party leaders.
